<br>
If it doesn't move then it may not move with you, but at least it cannot move against you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
First of all, only a very idiotic game designer would make such an extreme change to the state of the world as to invalidate peoples' roleplay.  However, I do not even necessarily see how the &quot;extreme change&quot; that you use an example would be any more hindering to roleplay than a completely static world.  Alliances shift, moods change, new things happen.  Roleplaying a dark elf or high elf who clings to old prejudgices and holds old grudges, while the rest of his/her society is moving towards a more cooperative and accepting attitude, would still be a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  completely</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> valid character to roleplay and in many ways it could only but open more oppurtunities and scenarios for you to enjoy as a roleplayer.  So you wouldn't be the stereotypical dark elf/high elf anymore, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  what's wrong with that?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Some of life's greatest dramas arise from how different people deal with change.<br>
<br>
 <p><B><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT></B><BR>
