<br>
And there I am afraid is your larger problem. We struggle to keep RP alive on FV, one of 20+ servers. The blue server population would have screaming fits if Freeport disappeared or the like. It is bad enough if they change a spawn rate, let alone dispense with it altogether. If there were a growing number of RP-preferred servers then our constituency would be greater for such changes. Heck, they couldn't even keep &quot;dynamic events&quot; going on SH and they had folks paying extra for them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utukka.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tukka</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 203<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/25/02 1:48:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2762.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.atlantic.net/~tukka/glowhand.jpg height=44 width=44></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Carthage</span><hr size=1> Well, my basic argument is that EverQuest was designed with little heed or consideration given to roleplay.  I think this is evident in zone design, character design, the game's backstory, the nature of scripted events, the nature of quests and the way the game has been marketed.<br>
<br>
People don't care about roleplay in large part because the game was not designed for roleplayers.  Even people who are inclined to roleplay (such as myself) have pretty much given up on it in EverQuest.<br>
<br>
As far as I'm concerned, there is very little they can do to improve the climate for RP without alienating the bulk of their customer base.  The original question posed was why people feel EQ lacks a coherant narrative, and I guess my answer is that the narrative that we all experience in the form of quests and general game environment is non-conducive to RP... it just serves as a adequate platform from which to launch various challenges.<br>
<br>
I know that by playing to the masses, Verant has pretty intentionally set down this road.  One of the rules of a virtual world is that the quality of roleplaying is inversely proportional to the number of players.   Oh well.  I'm not saying it's bad business sense, I'm just pointing out how this game is clearly not designed with roleplaying as a focus and how it is clearly lacking in this regard.<br>
<br>
I still think that there are things that they could have done (and they probably realize this in retrospect, hindsight is 20/20) to encourage and faccilitate roleplaying without alienating the masses, but it's too late to change things now. <p><B><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT></B><BR>
